<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,150,419]" pageId="4" pageNumber="263">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,262,289,315]" pageId="4" pageNumber="263">Note.</emphasis>
We were able to locate the jar but unfortunately the specimen was 
<taxonomicName box="[1016,1052,289,315]" class="Not" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="4" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="class">not</taxonomicName>
in the vial. In 1896, F.O. Pickard- Cambridge described the male stating that he did 
<taxonomicName box="[707,742,324,350]" class="Not" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="4" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="class">not</taxonomicName>
compared his specimen with the 
<typeStatus box="[1118,1168,324,350]" pageId="4" pageNumber="263">type</typeStatus>
, but he had no doubt of the identity of 
<taxonomicName box="[311,457,359,385]" class="Arachnida" family="Cyrtaucheniidae" genus="Fufius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="4" pageNumber="263" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="auricomus">
<emphasis box="[311,328,359,384]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="263">F</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[341,457,359,384]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="263">auricomus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with his female from Santarein. He also mentions that “The males have 
<taxonomicName box="[1251,1286,359,385]" class="Not" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="4" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="class">not</taxonomicName>
hitherto been described, but the two obtained on the lower Amazons undoubtedly belong to the females taken at the same time”.
</paragraph>
